<h2 id="ht">Miscellaneous .html notes </h2>
<ul><li> for in-page anchor links <i>href</i> is used not <i>src</i>. (only instance of latter so far is in <i>img</i>).
<li> ~ #later: "Very light blue eyes and big (not dark) bags. Permanent faint, red, streak across his left ear. Dark toes."
<li> to exclude in #css selectors use <i>:not()</i>. tipped via <a href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/16201948/how-to-exclude-particular-class-name-in-css-selector">stackoverflow</a>.
<li>Misspellings and forgets<table>
<tr><td>string 		<td>as.. 	<td>in syntax..
<tr><td>nth-child()	<td>nth-chld() <td>css
</table>
<li>
<li>

<li> 270814, <a href="http://css-tricks.com/child-and-sibling-selectors/">css-tricks.com</a> : sibling selectors <i>p+p+div</i> selects every <i>div</i> that is right after two consequent sibling <i>p</i> objects. general siblings, that is, sibling selectors non-consequent invoked by the tiladash(<i>~</i>) symbol.
<li>making the lovely separator glow..  "<i>box-shadow: 120px 80px 40px 20px #0ff; //
    	/* in order: x offset, y offset, blur size, spread size, color */
	/* blur size and spread size are optional (they default to 0) */</i>" 
courtesy of <a href="http://codersblock.com/blog/creating-glow-effects-with-css/">codersblock.com</a> after following leads from [random sources].
	<ul><li>- so basically: "box-shadow: x, y, blur, spread, color" with everything up until color being "px" type units. and no commas. #w
	<li>- odd thing. although <i>background-color</i> is set to transparent, the blurs and so on don't appear inside the <i>hr</i> object
		<ul><li>- or (just tested) a <i>div</i> object.. "only the inner shadow" is <i>:inset ..</i> as given by commentor at <a href="http://css-tricks.com/snippets/css/css-box-shadow/">css-tricks</a>. 
		<li>- same source of [codersblock.com] gave multiples of the configuration: comma-delimited properties. eg. <i>":box-shadow: 0 20px 120px 5px pink, 0 0 12px 2px green"</i> (beacuse of course giving the setting-id twice overwrites..doh-moment..)// #w
</ul></ul><li>~#later "Sweet lord. Emmet has got me grinning all morning"
<hr/>
<li> "If we make an element round with border-radius: 50%, then box-shadow will follow suit." -[codersblock.com]. 
	- <a href="http://www.w3schools.com/cssref/css3_pr_border-radius.asp">w3schools</a> has information on <strike>unit-types</strike> properties-types, including percentage, <i>"inherit"</i>, etc. 
	- A single unit defined apparently is automatic shorthand for every four corners of the object. 
	- <a href="http://www.css3.info/preview/rounded-border/">css3.info</a> image demos immediately help to clue in that they stand for the "(rounded) corners" explaining the % as akin to that in jaavscript canvases. 
		- "The first set of (1-4) values define the horizontal radii for all four corners. An optional second set of values, preceded by a /, define the vertical radii for all four corners. If only one set of values are supplied, these are used to determine both the vertical and horizontal equally." 
<i>border-radius: 5px 10px 5px 10px / 10px 5px 10px 5px;</i>
<li>keep forgetting that<i>font-family</i> property (and others) have to be applied to the <i>pre</i> tag rather than <i>body</i> overall.

<li> just had a genius(?) idea for <i>list-style-type</i> color: is there an "nth-character" type thing lying around? cue 
"We also get a couple of text-specific pseudo elements to help with our typography needs: <i>::first-letter, ::first-line</i>" -- <a href="http://css-tricks.com/a-call-for-nth-everything/">css-tricks.com</a>. _{darn griggin it. literally took input as "first letter of object". sigh.}
